&lt;p style="margin-bottom: 15px; font-style: italic;"&gt;Lawmakers are debating whether to extend subsidies that make health insurance affordable for millions of Americans, a policy that would cost roughly $85 billion over three years—and they say no. Yet at the same time, the Trump administration’s signature legislative achievement, the so-called One Big Beautiful Bill, showers the richest households with nearly $2.3 trillion in tax breaks over the next decade. That’s not just a quirk of budgeting; It’s a choice about whose needs matter in Washington and whose don’t.&lt;/p&gt;
